'''Stephen "Stig" Paul Abell'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://search.findmypast.co.uk/results/world-records/england-and-wales-births-1837-2006?firstname=stephen&lastname=abell%20&eventyear=1980&eventyear_offset=0|title=findmypast.co.uk|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://directors.findthecompany.co.uk/l/8652906/Mr-Stephen-Paul-Abell|title=Mr. Stephen Paul Abell (Stig Media Limited)|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://leveson.sayit.mysociety.org/speech/36340|title=“MR STEPHEN PAUL ABELL (affirme...” ::Leveson Inquiry :: SayIt|publisher=}}</ref> (born 10 April 1980) is an English [[journalist]], [[newspaper editor]] and [[radio presenter]]. 

Currently editor of ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'', Abell was the managing editor of the UK's ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|Sun]]'' newspaper from 2013 to 2016. He was formerly a fiction reviewer at ''[[The Spectator]]'' and reviewer at [[Telegraph Media Group]] as well as ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]''. In addition to this he was formerly a presenter on [[LBC|LBC Radio]].

==Education==
Abell was born in [[Nottingham]] and educated at [[Loughborough Grammar School]], and went on to graduate with a double first in English from [[Emmanuel College, Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newscommercial.co.uk/news/stephen-abell-appointed-managing-editor-of-the-sun|title=News Commercial - Home|publisher=newscommercial.co.uk|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref>

==Career==
In September 2001, Abell joined the [[Press Complaints Commission]] as a complaints officer;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journalism.co.uk/news/pcc-appoints-stephen-abell-as-new-director/s2/a536372/ |title=PCC appoints Stephen Abell as new director |publisher=journalism.co.uk |date=5 November 2009 |accessdate=6 November 2009}}</ref> he completed other roles at the PCC including press officer, assistant director and deputy director before being appointed Director of the PCC on 19 December 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.linkedin.com/pub/stig-abell/0/491/4a9 |title=Stephen Abell Linked In Profile |publisher=[[Linked in]] |date=13 August 2013 |accessdate=14 August 2013}}</ref>
In August 2013, Abell joined ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' as Managing Editor, his role until the end of April 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journalism.co.uk/news/pcc-appoints-stephen-abell-as-new-director/s2/a536372/ |title=Stephen Abell appointed Managing Editor of The Sun |publisher=News UK |date=26 August 2013 |accessdate=27 August 2013}}</ref>

In March 2014, Abell started co-presenting a show on [[LBC|LBC Radio]] alongside [[Sky News]] television presenter [[Kay Burley]] from 8{{nbsp}}am to 11{{nbsp}}am on Sundays. Burley was the main presenter while Abell reviewed the papers and added political comment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lbc.co.uk/kay-burley--stig-abell-87717 |title=Kay Burley & Stig Abell |publisher= [[LBC Radio]] |date=24 March 2014 |accessdate=27 March 2014}}</ref>

From August 2014, the show was co-presented by Abell and LBC's [[Petrie Hosken]]. In January 2015, he was given his own show from 8{{nbsp}}am to 10{{nbsp}}am on Sundays. From April 2016, Abell moved to the afternoon slot on Sundays of 3{{nbsp}}pm to 6{{nbsp}}pm.

In May 2016, Abell took up a new post as the editor of ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]'', succeeding [[Peter Stothard|Sir Peter Stothard]], who had edited the newspaper for the previous 14 years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2016/feb/12/sun-managing-editor-stig-abell-to-become-editor-of-the-tls|title=Sun managing editor Stig Abell to become editor of the TLS|last=Greenslade|first=Roy|date=12 February 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=30 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.co.uk/2016/02/stig-abell-appointed-ediorpublisher-of-the-times-literary-supplement/#|title=Stig Abell appointed Editor/Publisher of the Times Literary Supplement {{!}} News UK|website=www.news.co.uk|access-date=30 March 2016}}</ref> He is a regular presenter on the [[BBC Radio Four]] series ''[[Front Row (radio)|Front Row]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.noelgay.com/client/stig-abell-2/|title=Stig Abell - NOEL GAY|website=www.noelgay.com|language=en-GB|access-date=3 January 2018}}</ref>

In May 2018, he published his first book entitled “How Britain Really Works”.

